shared_text:
Tishomingo Child Nutrition
Yesterday at 9:17 AM ·

Tishomingo County Schools are happy to announce that beginning Monday, September 14, 2020, we will begin providing FREE meals (Breakfast and Lunch) to all students regardless of what their previous cafeteria status has been - Free, Reduced, or Paid. This has been made possible through funding from USDA and will be available as long as funds are available or until December 2020.

The district will continue to process free/reduced lunch applications. If you haven’t already completed an application, please do so. This can be done online or one can be sent home with your child.

We are excited about the opportunity to feed our children healthy meals each day for free.
Please call Amy B. Cornelius, Child Nutrition Director, if you have any questions at 662-423-3206.

The TCSD is an equal opportunity provider.

post_text: "Due to Governor Reeves' Executive Order 1517, all staff and students are required to wear facial coverings or masks while on buses, while on any school campus, and while inside any school buildings. If you have already enrolled your child as a distance learner but would like to switch him/her to a traditional student, please contact your child's school to inform them of this decision. The district has posted a statement regarding masks on its website and social media accounts to help address questions you may have. We appreciate your patience and understanding as we work through these changing times. Thank you and stay safe!"

The Tishomingo County School District will change its “grab and go” breakfast/lunch pick up times to Monday and Wednesday ONLY beginning Monday, March 30th. • Burnsville Elementary

post_text: This is a reminder that school is cancelled from March 16-20. All activities and practices are cancelled as well. Staff will report on Friday, March 20th. An update email has been sent to staff and needs to be read before arriving on the 20th. Plans will be made tomorrow to begin serving grab and go breakfast and lunches for students beginning Tuesday. Information will be sent tomorrow about locations and pickup times. The CDC has asked the public to avoid traveling domestically at this time. If you don’t have to travel, stay home. These precautions are to prevent COVID-19 spread to those in our community who have pre-existing health conditions and the elderly. Let’s work together to stay healthy and promote wellness to our community! We will update as the situation changes.

post_text: Due to positive confirmation in MS for COVID-19 (coronavirus), TCSD will not allow field trips to in state conventions or out of state events until further notice. We will send our action plan for our district to faculty and parents next week. This is a precautionary measure. Other activities will continue as normal. As always, if staff and students feel sick or show signs of sickness, they should stay home. We want to keep perspective with this outbreak but also use precaution since young people and healthy adults seem to recover from the virus very well while elderly or adults with health conditions struggle. The health and safety of our students and staff are always our top priority, and we will follow guidance from CDC, MDH, MDE, and local doctors in making decisions concerning this virus.

post_text: The Tishomingo County School District recently missed 5 school days due to inclement weather and unsafe road conditions. The District will use February 19, 2018 (Presidents' Day), and April 2, 2018 (Good Monday), as make up days to gain instructional time before end-of-year assessments. School will be in session on these days. March 19, 2018 will remain a professional development day. Staff will attend school that day, but students will not. The other 3 days that were missed will be forgiven due to authority given to the superintendent and school board in district policy and state statute. If any additional days are missed, changes to this plan may occur.

post_text:
Attention Parents of School-Aged Kids:

With extra days off of school, it would be a great time to wash your child’s jackets, backpacks, shoes, etc. and help us fight the spread of the flu. You can also wipe down their lunch boxes, binders, and other surfaces with Clorox or Lysol wipes. Help keep colds and flu out of school!

At TCSD our teachers are wiping down desks and spraying Lysol before and after the kids leave. We are disinfecting surfaces such as water fountains, light switches, counters and any high touched areas. We are providing Germ-X, tissues and encouraging hand-washing. We had hoped that the Christmas break would give the flu time to die down but it did not. We are doing all that we know to do, so anything you can do at home to try to help is greatly appreciated. Stay safe and be well!
text:
Attention Parents of School-Aged Kids:

With extra days off of school, it would be a great time to wash your child’s jackets, backpacks, shoes, etc. and help us fight the spread of the flu. You can also wipe down their lunch boxes, binders, and other surfaces with Clorox or Lysol wipes. Help keep colds and flu out of school!

At TCSD our teachers are wiping down desks and spraying Lysol before and after the kids leave. We are disinfecting surfaces such as water fountains, light switches, counters and any high touched areas. We are providing Germ-X, tissues and encouraging hand-washing. We had hoped that the Christmas break would give the flu time to die down but it did not. We are doing all that we know to do, so anything you can do at home to try to help is greatly appreciated. Stay safe and be well!
